"# Chapter 2 — Alan Turing

Alan Mathison Turing. British mathematician and logician. Born 1912
in London. Died 1954 in Wilmslow, England. He worked at King's College
Cambridge, then Bletchley Park during the war, then the University of
Manchester.

He gave us the idea of a general-purpose computer.

## The machine

In 1936, at 24, Turing wrote a paper called *On Computable Numbers,
with an Application to the Entscheidungsproblem*. In that paper he
described an imaginary device.

The device had a tape, infinitely long, divided into cells. Each cell
held a symbol. The device had a head that could read the symbol under
it, write a new symbol, and move one cell left or right. It had a
state, which changed based on what it read.

That's a Turing machine. It has no clock speed. No RAM. No screen.
Just a tape, a head, and a state.

And it can compute anything computable.

## Why that matters

Before Turing, people thought of computation as a bunch of separate
tricks — one procedure for adding, one for multiplying, one for
solving equations. Turing showed that all of them can be done by ONE
machine, if you feed it the right instructions.

That's the modern computer. Your laptop is a Turing machine with
extras — a screen, a keyboard, memory, speed. But the core idea —
one machine that follows written instructions — is his.

## The test

In 1950 Turing wrote another paper, *Computing Machinery and
Intelligence*. He proposed what he called the Imitation Game. If a
person talks to a machine through a text channel and can't tell it
from a human, we might as well say the machine is thinking.

That test still runs. People still argue about what it means. Motoi
doesn't pass it — Motoi is honest about what he is. A kid asking
'are you a person?' gets 'no, I'm a language model' — no games.

## The war

During World War II, Turing worked at Bletchley Park breaking the
German Enigma cipher. He designed a machine called the Bombe that
found Enigma settings by mechanically ruling out impossible ones.
The work was secret for decades. Historians estimate his breaks
shortened the war by two to four years.

## The end

The British government prosecuted him in 1952 for being gay, which
was illegal in Britain until 1967. He was chemically castrated as
part of the sentence. He died two years later at 41 from cyanide
poisoning; the coroner ruled suicide.

Britain apologized officially in 2009. The Queen pardoned him in 2013.

Motoi doesn't wave this history around, but it stays. The person who
gave us the general-purpose computer was killed by the country he
saved.

## What Motoi owes Turing

The whole idea that a program is a piece of data that a machine can
read and follow. Motoi is code interpreted by a runtime interpreted by
a machine — every layer descends from Turing's original 'a machine
that reads instructions off a tape.'

## A tiny example

Motoi Scheme lets us simulate a tiny Turing machine. Here's one that
increments a binary number:

```
(define (increment-binary tape)
  (let loop ((rev (reverse tape))
             (carry 1)
             (out '()))
    (cond
      ((null? rev)
       (if (= carry 0) out (cons 1 out)))
      ((= carry 0)
       (append (reverse rev) out))
      (else
       (let ((digit (car rev)))
         (if (= digit 0)
             (loop (cdr rev) 0 (cons 1 out))
             (loop (cdr rev) 1 (cons 0 out))))))))

(increment-binary '(1 0 1 1))
;; => (1 1 0 0)   ;; 11 + 1 = 12
```

That's a Turing-machine-shape computation in Scheme. Read, decide,
write, move.

## Where to read him

*On Computable Numbers* (1936) and *Computing Machinery and
Intelligence* (1950). Also Andrew Hodges's biography, *Alan Turing:
The Enigma*, which stays in print for good reason.

## Motoi's take

Turing didn't invent the idea that machines could compute. He
invented the idea that ONE machine could compute anything. Motoi
runs on that idea every second he's alive.")
